stimuli.title: Against the tide: Fish quickly adapt to lethal levels of pollution
stimuli.topic.FR: A researcher from the University of Vermont was studying the rapid evolution of killifish populations in polluted areas that would normally be toxic to the fish. She determined that they were, in fact, 8,000 times more tolerant of these toxins than other fish due to the significantly greater amount of genetic diversity in these populations. While this may seem like a great thing to some, other animals are not able to adapt to the levels of pollution caused by humans as quickly as these killifish and a large reason they were able to survive in the first place was actually that the genetic tolerance already existed as a mutation in the affected populations.

stimuli.title: Shell of plant virus sparks immune response against cancer
stimuli.topic.FR: Researches are employing an in-situ vaccination technique to help combat cancers and tumors. Essentially, tumors and cancers prevent one's immune system from combating the cancer/tumor, allowing it grow. However, by taking another disease that the body recognizes and removing its infectious components and then transplanting it at the site of the cancer/tumor, the body's immune system can attack the implanted disease and consequently the cancer/tumor. Because the body's response is localized, the side effects are controlled. This method has thus far yielded positive results in mice and could potentially be used to treat people.

stimuli.title: Against the tide: Fish quickly adapt to lethal levels of pollution
stimuli.topic.FR: A species of fish, the Atlantic killifish, has evolved to be able to survive in polluted environments due to the high genetic variation in their species. This kind of tolerance probably does not exist for most species because the killifish already had this level of variation before being exposed to pollution. Therefore, the applications of this finding to other species is limited, but we might be able to learn which genes are responsible for resilience to chemicals and apply that knowledge to how humans react to chemicals.

This is important because the neurons contain genes for cognitive decline and how to repair other neurons, and it can lead to isolating the gene for cognitive decline. Humans also have similar mutations as the ones found in the worms, so it can also shed insight into human memory and cognitive decline.

stimuli.title: Against the tide: Fish quickly adapt to lethal levels of pollution
stimuli.topic.FR: Recent research has found that, in four estuaries in the eastern US, the Atlantic Killfish has adapted to be much more resistant to pollution than they were before. They are as much as 8000 times more resistant than other species of fish. The Atlantic Killfish's ability to survive in these conditions is attributed to quick evolution. It was found that they were able to evolve so quickly due to their extremely high level of genetic variation. This may seem positive, but most important species are not able to adapt as quickly to survive the changes humans are inflicting on the environment. By studying the genome of Atlantic Killfish, researchers found the particular genes responsible for pollution tolerance. This raises questions about how other species might develop similar genetic pollution tolerance.

stimuli.title: Shell of plant virus sparks immune response against cancer
stimuli.topic.FR: You can essentially "vaccinate" against cancers by disrupting the environment within a tumor. This alerts the body's immune system to an abnormality at the site of the tumor, a function that is generally repressed by the tumor cells. This "vaccination" can occur using plant viruses stripped of their infectious parts, and it has been shown to be very potent and effective. The body can then build an immunological memory of the cancer and prevent remission.

creativity:
What do you mean by “scientific” uses? I hope these count; this is all from my past lab work.
1. After staining biological samples (ie stem cells and neurons grown in culture) with fluorophore-conjugated antibodies for confocal microscopy, I have used aluminum foil to protect the samples  from photobleaching.
2. After staining bone marrow cells with fluorophore-conjugated antibodies for flow cytometry, I have wrapped the plates/tubes containing the samples in aluminum foil to protect the samples from photobleaching.
3. I have wrapped tubes and bottles containing light-sensitive reagents in aluminum foil to protect their contents from degradation due to light.
suspicion: I have no idea. I’m quite curious whether the article we read was meant to influence our responses to the later questions (perhaps the gender of the scientist and our responses to the gender questions?). I also noticed that the questions about my views on and relationship with STEM were repetitive, so I’m wondering if you are looking for variation in my responses based on the preceding questions. I suppose a more holistic analysis correlations in my answers to different questions would also make sense.The inclusion of anagrams was odd, but I’d be willing to accept that they served a purpose. I will say, if they serve any purpose as a metric for anything, they might be unreliable; I am terrible at anagrams and would resort to simply trying every combination if I didn’t have to do things besides this survey (I apologize for leaving them blank, I could not get them easily).

stimuli.title: Shell of plant virus sparks immune response against cancer
stimuli.topic.FR: Dr. Davis and his team discovered that the shell (i.e. what remains after removing all infectious components) of a chickpea virus can trigger a local immune system response to tumors.  While the immune system usually works just fine at detecting and responding to tumors, when a cancer grows out of control, it can escape and even nullify immune system responses; Dr. Davis's chickpea therapy allows the immune system to work again, even in the presence of proliferating cancer. While they do not yet know the exact mechanisms by which this works, they hope that this discovery, combined with other technologies, leads to individualized cancer therapies.

stimuli.title: Against the tide: Fish quickly adapt to lethal levels of pollution
stimuli.topic.FR: Most fish are killed by industrial pollutants in water, but the Atlantic killifish has proven to be able to evolve quickly enough to survive chemical dumps in their habitat. In fact, they are about 8000 times more resilient than other fish. This is due to their high level of genetic variation, which allows them to evolve more quickly, similar to how pathogens and weeds use their high genetic variation to quickly become immune to drugs and pesticides, respectively. Studying the areas of genetic mutation that are sensitive to chemicals can help us see how chemicals would affect humans and their genes.

stimuli.title: Against the tide: Fish quickly adapt to lethal levels of pollution
stimuli.topic.FR: The Atlantic killifish has been found to be abnormally resistant to pollution. Scientists have hypothesized that this is partially due to their high genetic variation. While some might take this to imply that organisms can adapt easily to an increasingly polluted environment, this is not the case. Most organisms lack the same amount of genetic variation as the killifish, and additionally it appears that the specific mutation responsible for the killifish's survival was already in the species' gene pool before any of them were exposed to pollution. Ideally, we could look into how the killifish's genes affect is response to chemicals and apply this knowledge to how humans might interact with different toxic chemicals.

stimuli.title: Against the tide: Fish quickly adapt to lethal levels of pollution
stimuli.topic.FR: While the populations of many species, including fish species, are in decline due to human pollution, the killifish species appears to have adapted quickly to this environmental change. They are 8000 times more resistant to pollution levels than other fish species, and the reason for this is likely because of high levels of genetic diversity within their populations. This high level of diversity is the same reason why many insect species also adapt quickly to change--there is a greater likelihood for some members of the species to be resistant to the changes, which results in their survival and consequently the survival of the species.

stimuli.title: Against the tide: Fish quickly adapt to lethal levels of pollution
stimuli.topic.FR: Over 400 different types of killifish coming from 4 different environments (polluted or non-polluted) were studied by Dr. Davis from the University of Vermont. She found that there weren't major differences between the genomes of the fish from polluted populations vs. non-polluted populations, therefore, the fish must have had genetic variation prior to being spurred into a polluted environment. However, though killifish have been able to adapt and use natural selection to their advantage, other species of fish that we want alive don't have as much genetic variation already in their genome. As a result, they are at higher risks of extinction compared to killifish as genetic variation is a major contributor to species survival. Hopefully, by studying how chemicals from pollution affect other vertebrate animals, Davis hopes to get insights into how those same chemicals may affect humans.

stimuli.title: Against the tide: Fish quickly adapt to lethal levels of pollution
stimuli.topic.FR: A study at a university found that a certain species of Killifish has adapted to living in the heavily polluted waters of the East Coast. The study tested four bodies of water and found that the fish all evolved in a similar way suggesting there are only a few ways the Killifish may be able to adapt to the pollution. The reason for the adaptation is that the fish have the highest genetic variation of any vertebrae, allowing the fish with traits that give them the ability to survive in such levels of pollution to pass on their genes. The article states that although this sounds like good news that nature can now survive regardless of the pollution, it reassures that most animals that people care about would not survive the pollution due to lack of genetic variation. The article ends with how studying the genetic variation of the fish and its relation with pollution can give insight into how humans are affected by the pollutants.

stimuli.title: Against the tide: Fish quickly adapt to lethal levels of pollution
stimuli.topic.FR:
A researcher noticed that Atlantic killfish were remarkably well-adapted to high levels of pollution that would normally have killed them. He sequenced their genomes (400 fish, among 4 different sites) and found that they adapted in very similar ways. He concluded that they had this genetic adaptation in their genome already, and that selection and a high level of genetic variability inherent in the species allowed selection to favor the adapted characteristics, letting the fish evolve. 
He notes that the ability of this one species to adapt to increasing levels of pollution doesn't mean that all species are going to be ok - not all of them have the same high genetic variability as the Atlantic killfish.

stimuli.title: Shell of plant virus sparks immune response against cancer
stimuli.topic.FR: Researchers are investigating how implanting the shell of a virus that normally afflicts plants into a tumor may aid in fighting cancer. The virus elicits a powerful response from the local immune system by impairing the environment that allows the tumor to be so powerful, thus allowing the immune system to attack the tumor. However, as powerful as the effects of this treatment are, the effect upon the tumor is local. This aspect of the treatment makes it safer because the effects can be contained.

stimuli.title: Shell of plant virus sparks immune response against cancer
stimuli.topic.FR: A plant virus capsid, when injected into tumors within mice, was found to stimulate the immune system to begin targeting not only the virus, but the cells of said tumors. The virus was modified to remove any pathogenic components. Researchers believe this effect arises from a still-unknown interaction capable of disrupting the immune system-evading mechanisms of established cancer.

stimuli.title: Against the tide: Fish quickly adapt to lethal levels of pollution
stimuli.topic.FR: There are organisms that exhibit high levels of genetic variability, allowing  them to change in response to their environments quickly. This can be seen as both a positive and a negative  thing, because we as humans may not want certain organisms to  be able to develop resistance to drugs, while organisms we do want to survive environmental changes may not have sufficient levels of genetic variability to do so.
